Firstly, it is estimated that there are not more than 100,000 health workers in Kenya. It is, therefore, quite straightforward to ensure that they are given priority in order to reduce the risk to themselves and to those that come into contact with them.
Other high-risk frontliners like police and teachers should then be considered for prioritisation depending on their deployment status. This first phase of prioritisation is aimed at ensuring continuity of vital social services while limiting the risk of spread of the virus in the population by targeting the high-risk segments.
Secondly, our vaccination strategy must aim at protecting those at greatest risk of death, in our case those aged 60 years and above. We estimate these elders to be about two million in our population, and even if we were only able to vaccinate those, we would significantly reduce the deaths related to Covid-19.
The other important population to protect would then be those with underlying conditions such as diabetes and hypertension. Unfortunately a huge proportion of our population has these conditions, and most of those remain undiagnosed.
Our vaccination strategy must, therefore, treat these on a case-by-case basis, by creating an algorithm that stratifies risk and prioritises those at highest risk of death and severe disease.



